<TITLE> UEFA announces big increase in Euro prize money </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LUCERNE, Switzerland, Dec 2 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The teams taking part in Euro 2008 will receive a substantial increase in prize money compared with the last tournament, UEFA said on Saturday. European soccer's governing body has made 184 million euros ($271.3 million) available for the 16 qualifiers competing to be European champions, compared with 129 million at Euro 2004. All teams at the tournament being co-hosted by Austria and Switzerland next June will get 7.5 million euros, compared with 4.8 million each at the previous finals in Portugal. In the group phase there will be performance bonuses of one million euros for a win and 500,000 euros for a draw. The quarter-finalists will each receive an additional payment of two million euros, while the semi-finalists can look forward to an extra reward of three million euros. The team crowned European champions at the Ernst-Happel Stadium on June 29 will get an additional 7.5 million euros with the runners-up receiving another 4.5 million. If the Euro 2008 winners have also won all three of their group matches they will receive total prize money of 23 million euros compared with 17.7 million at the last finals
